This workflow utilises the ControlNet OpenPose model, TwoSamplersForMask (from Impact Pack) and the Clipspace feature of ComfyUI to generate images with Lora models applied to specific areas of the picture.

#############################################################################
 ---------------------------------HOW TO USE--------------------------------
#############################################################################
1) Set {Workflow Mode} in [Gloval Settings & Conditioning] to 'Prepare Pose' 
   mode
2) Generate an image while watching the {OpenPose Preprocessor Output} and 
   {Mask Editor} Preview Bridge nodes at the bottom of [Area & Pose]. Cancel 
   generation once they update (the cyan/orange nodes in [Global Settings & 
   Conditioning] will be used for this generation)
3) If a desired pose was generated and the OpenPose Preprocessor did a good 
   enough job detecting both characters, proceed to step #4. Otherwise, revert 
   to step #2.
4) a) Set {Workflow Mode} in [Gloval Settings & Conditioning] to 'Generate 
      Image' mode
   b) On {Mask Editor} node: right click -> Open in MaskEditor -> Draw mask 
   over one of the characters
5) All preparation is now done, you can generate your image(s). Subject #1 will be generated on the area not marked with the mask, while Subject #2 on the marked area. The 'Background' prompts will cover the entire image but seem to have a very low effect.

#############################################################################
 --------------------------------TIPS & TRICKS------------------------------
#############################################################################
 - Use a realistic checkpoint for 'Prepare Pose' mode, as it makes it easier for the OpenPose Preprocessor. 2.5D anime checkpoints should be ok too.
 - With hand detection enabled in {OpenposePreprocessor} in [Area & Pose] better results can be achieved if the hands are properly detected.
 - If the OpenPose Preprocessor detects both faces as one, which can happen often with kisses and also sometimes with hugs, as long as the edge of the mask goes near the detected position of the nose (which it should), this will have no negative effect on the images generated in 'Generate Image' mode
 - When drawing the mask over/around body parts that cross over the other character (eg. arms in a hug), giving the body part a bit more space than the generated body part would suggest seems to give better results
 - It is a good practice to draw the mask not only over a character but also the background around them so that their hair and clothes have more room.
 - Especially when using a different style of Loras for subjects, there sometimes appears a seam in the background where the two areas border each other. This is usually fixed in 2nd Pass, but the backgrounds behind each subject won't be unified, the transition from one to the other will simply make more sense, while staying clearly visible

#############################################################################
 ------------------------------TECHNICAL NOTES------------------------------
#############################################################################
 - Due to some limitations in ComfyUI, a pose image will still be generated in 'Generate Image' mode. To alleviate the time this consumes, it is set to generate 64x64 images while in 'Generate Image' mode.
   - To prevent that image from replacing those in {OpenPose Preprocessor Output} and {Mask Editor} a somewhat hacky solution is implemented using Impact Pack's ImageSender and ImageReceiver nodes. This, however, results in the staggering of those images by one 'Queue Prompt' before they reach {OpenPose Preprocessor Output} and {Mask Editor}. This means that it will take two queued prompts for the first image to get there every time after switching to 'Prepare Pose' mode.

#############################################################################
 -----------------------------ITERATIVE UPSCALE-----------------------------
#############################################################################
Iterative upscale (from Impact Pack) in [2nd Pass] upscales the image in smaller increments and passes it through a sampler on each step, resulting in better quality and detail at the cost of speed.
 - {Upscale Factor} decides the final size increase
 - {Upscale steps} decide the number of steps in which upscaling is divided. If set to 1 it is identical to normal upscaling.

If set for example to Upscale Factor = 2, Upscale Steps = 4, then it will do the following: upscale 1.25, sampler pass, upscale 1.5, sampler pass, upscale 1.75, sampler pass, upscale 2, sampler pass (upscale values are relative to original size)

#############################################################################
 -----------------------------------OTHER-----------------------------------
#############################################################################
 - Black nodes are switches that enable/disable certain functions and switch between certain options (eg. upscaling using latent upscale vs an upscale model)

 - With 2 faces, face restoration will run twice, once for each face, prolonging generation time. Just a heads up.

- Grid Size for this workflow is 25
